comments.commentBody:
@bakes: I didn't even think it WAS a foul. Rodwell got to the ball first. He's supremely talented, but the meal Suarez made out of that challenge was an absolute disgrace, and he does it all...the...time.  guess it's taken a little time, but you've been vindicated about the warts showng on Charlie Adam. And King Kenny finally recognized that he should play Kuyt over Jordan Henderson. But Downing didn't do much on his shift out there. As soon as SG and Bellamy came on, Pool was another team entirely, and had much more than their poor neighbors.<br/>
As for Inter, Obi's first challenge was very much like the Rodwell challenge, but he got the ball and hooked it away, and was booked. But he had the chance to play with caution once booked, which was denied to Rodwell. It was a professional foul that dismissed Obi on his second yellow, but the push from behind was clearly outside the box, and the Napoli man staggered like a drunk heading for the last bus in Dublin (where I was an exchange student, and did it myself many times...) before falling comically. I guess since he was on a card, it WAS a dismissal, but never a PK.<br/>
TDK might want to weigh in on Inter's complete capitulaton. First question I have, is Sneijder hurt, or is he just pouting? Inter has Forlan, Pazzini and Zarate to attack. They never should look as bereft of attackng ideas as they did, particularly in the second half. TDK was spot on-the best attacks were from Maicon, Lucio and, to a lesser extent, Zanetti. That midfield was overwhelmed by Napoli. Before Juve got two late to beat Milan, I was looking at the table, amazed to see, before Juve leapt top, Udinese, Palermo, Napoli and Cagliari. And Atalanta would be tied there, had they not been deducted sx points for the fixing charges. Cold sweat on both sides of Milan. Early on, Napoli looks the most complete side. Don't discount Mascara, who was the best player and captain of Catania the last few years and is a very good player, particularly off the bench.
